Rating: 2
The recipe is something to start from and has potential, but, much like AKUMATENDO, I felt there was something missing just from the ingredients. So, I sauteed some onions with the garlic and some fire roasted jalapenos from my garden and Fresh Cilantro. I then added a bit more butter for the fat coating of the rice and sauteed the rice til the eyes of the rice were apparent. I added the corn (which I fire roasted as well, you can also buy fire roasted frozen corn at Trader Joes) Then I added the chicken broth, half a cup at a time and it was already warming (this is proper Risotto technique by the way). I had some Salvadorian style Chorizo that I had already cooked and crumbled and had drained of any excess fat (appx 3/4 cup) that I added along with the cheese (yes, use a bit less and then top with Cotija or Queso Fresco when you serve along with more fresh cilantro) and the cream (already warmed). I served this with a beautiful chicken breast that was topped with a Poblano Cream Sauce...An amazing meal!

Rating: 3
This was a delicious alternative to standard mexican rice. I served it with the Tequila marinated Tri Tip and my whole family loved it. However, the dish does need some tweaking. I added 1/2 c finely chopped onion and 1/2 a chopped red jalapeno to the garlic and cumin (I used 1/2 tsp) saute. Let the onion get very soft before adding the rice. Let the rice cook a minute before adding 1 cup chicken broth. I added the corn and then proceeded to make the risotto the right way--1/2 cup of broth at a time, 1 qt broth in total. After all the broth was absorbed, I added 3/4 c cheese, which I thought was just right, cilantro and some chopped fresh oregano that I happened to have on hand.

